<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-593-807  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 593 807.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Nov 5 1990 v24 n44 p143(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>For minimal scanning needs, consider handheld scanners.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Keyes, Jessica.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Businesses and individuals with the infrequent need to scan imagesor printed material into microcomputers should consider purchasinga handheld scanner.andP;  While considered by some to be imprecise andinappropriate for processing large amounts of information,handheld scanners are available at prices between $200 and $600,offering considerable savings over prices for high-end desktopmodels.andP;  Buyers opting for handheld scanners should seek productsfeaturing changeable resolution settings and both top-to-bottomand side-to-side scanning.andP;  The most common desktop publishingfile formats for scanned images are PCX and Tag Image File Format;good handheld scanners should use one of the two.andP;  The ability to'train' a scanner to recognize new fonts is another desirablescanner function.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Scanning DevicesPurchasesGuidelines.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Top-selling handheld scanners. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>